result_summary.diagnosis_reasoning: 1) Match: The patient has active vomiting and objective moderate dehydration, which directly meet criteria for deficient fluid volume. The low–normal K+ (3.60 mmol/L) is consistent with early electrolyte shifts from fluid/GI losses. 2) Priority: No evidence of airway, breathing, or circulation compromise is provided; thus, per Maslow, physiological hydration needs take precedence. An actual problem (deficient fluid volume) outranks risk diagnoses (e.g., risk for electrolyte imbalance, risk for deficient fluid volume) and non–life-threatening alternatives. While dysfunctional gastrointestinal motility may be present (vomiting, retained contrast), the immediate threat to perfusion and homeostasis from fluid loss is higher priority. 3) Evidence: Ongoing vomiting, examiner-noted moderate dehydration, and borderline potassium support current volume deficit; excess fluid volume and perioperative risk diagnoses are not supported by the data.
